                        <foliation>
                           <p>The manuscript is foliated by <name type="person" key="JonSig004">Jón
                                 Sigurðsson</name> in the top right-hand corner (fols <locus
                                 from="1" to="19">1-19</locus>) or top margins (fols <locus
                                 from="19" to="64">19-64</locus>) of the recto pages.</p>
                        </foliation>
                        <collation>
                           <p>8 quires of 8 leaves.</p>
                        </collation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>The part of the codex preserved is in a good condition. The manuscript
                              ends defectively. According to Johnsen and Jón Helgason (<bibl>
                                 <ref type="secondary" target="OlHJH">Den store Saga om Olav den
                                    Hellige</ref>
                                 <biblScope unit="pages">891</biblScope>
                              </bibl>), the lacuna consists of 13 to 14 leaves. A part of the text
                              on fol. <locus>7v</locus> is effaced and fols <locus>29</locus> and
                                 <locus>52</locus> are partly damaged with loss of text, a few
                              others have tears and holes.</p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" writtenLines="35 40">
                           <p>The manuscript is written in long lines with 35 to 40 lines to each
                              page. Rubrics are in red. The verses in the text are generally marked
                              by a <q>v</q> in the margin.</p>
                           <p>The initials are either red, green or blue or green/red or blue/red.
                              The writer has originally left empty spaces for the initials and added
                              instructions for the insertion in the margin. These have been cut away
                              almost everywhere, but can still be seen on fols <locus>41v</locus>,
                                 <locus from="42v" to="43v">42v-43v</locus>, <locus>44v</locus> and
                                 <locus>56r</locus>.</p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc hands="1">
                     <handNote scope="sole" script="textualis">
                        <p>The manuscript is written in a neat and compressed Icelandic Gothic
                           bookhand. The writer has made an effort to save space, which can also be
                           seen by his very great use of abbreviations. He does not only use the
                           usual abbreviations, but also omits the endings of words which he
                           indicates with a bar. The hand is thought to be identical with that of
                              <title type="uniform" xml:lang="la">Codex Regius</title> (<ref
                              type="ms">GKS 2367 4to</ref>).</p>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="miniature">
                        <p>Fol. <locus>1r</locus>: Full-length pen-drawing of the enthroned St <name
                              type="person">Ólafr</name> wearing a flowing mantle and a hallowed
                           crown, holding an orb in his left hand and an axe in his right. An
                           imploring figure is lying prostrated under his feet (Satan or a
                           blasphemer?). A turreted building or a church has been drawn behind
                           Ólafr. Above Ólafr can be read: <q xml:lang="is">olafr
                              k<ex>onun</ex>gr</q>.</p>
                     </decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions>
                     <p>Marginalia in Icelandic and Norwegian/Danish occur. <list>
                           <item>Fol. <locus>1r</locus>: In addition to the drawing of <name
                                 type="person">St Ólafr</name>, there are also verses in Icelandic
                              from <date notBefore="1450" notAfter="1499">the second half of the
                                 fifteenth century</date> or <date notBefore="1500" notAfter="1515"
                                 >the beginning of the sixteenth</date>. The first verse on the
                              right side of the picture of King Ólafr reads: <q xml:lang="is"
                                    >olaf<ex>ur</ex> k<ex>o</ex>ngr noreg<supplied
                                    reason="illegible">i</supplied>
                                 <lb n="2"/> red likan<ex>n</ex> h<ex>an</ex>s <supplied
                                    reason="damage">hefi</supplied>
                                 <lb n="3"/> e<ex>k</ex> aunguan sied h<supplied reason="damage"
                                    >af</supplied>
                                 <lb n="4"/>n<ex>ar</ex> þor <choice>
                                    <sic>e<ex>r</ex>
                                    </sic>
                                    <corr>en</corr>
                                 </choice> heidr<ex>ar</ex> kri<supplied reason="damage"
                                    >st</supplied>
                                 <lb n="5"/> hafdi h<ex>ann</ex> alld<ex>ri</ex> lang<supplied
                                    reason="damage">a</supplied>
                                 <lb n="6"/> vist</q>. The second verse below the picture reads: <q
                                 xml:lang="is">Biarne h<ex>re</ex>ppe blezan erna bi<ex>ar</ex>na
                                 hialpe d<ex>ro</ex>ttin gi<ex>ar</ex>na bi<ex>ar</ex>na <gap
                                    unit="words" extent="1" reason="illegible"/> betrs <gap
                                    unit="words" extent="2" reason="illegible"/>
                                 <lb n="2"/> bi<ex>ar</ex>na <gap unit="words" extent="1"
                                    reason="illegible"/> godu u<ex>ar</ex>ne bi<ex>ar</ex>ne hliote
                                    b<ex>rv</ex>de kiorna biarna re<gap reason="illegible"/>
                                    sti<ex>ar</ex>na biarne <lb n="3"/> d<ex>re</ex>cke bior af
                                    h<ex>or</ex>nu<ex>m</ex> biarna alld<ex>ri</ex> uin<ex>er</ex>
                                 se f<ex>ar</ex>n<ex>er</ex>
                              </q>.</item>
                           <item>
                              <locus>29v</locus> A contemporary marginal note reads: <q
                                 xml:lang="la">aue maria gr<ex>aci</ex>a plena
                                    d<ex>omi</ex>n<ex>u</ex>s</q>.</item>
                        </list>
                        <list>
                           <head>Norwegian marginal notes from <date notBefore="1500"
                                 notAfter="1599">the sixteenth century</date> occur on:</head>
                           <item>Fol. <locus>4v</locus>: <q xml:lang="no">
                                 <supplied reason="damage">O</supplied>lafr tryggeß <lb n="2"/>
                                 <supplied reason="damage">v</supplied>or gudfad<supplied
                                    reason="omitted">er</supplied>
                                 <lb n="3"/>
                                 <supplied reason="damage">O</supplied>. hins helge</q>. </item>
                           <item>Fol. <locus>6v</locus>: <q xml:lang="no">gangerolf <lb/>
                                 <supplied reason="illegible">nam</supplied> nor<lb/>mandia</q>. </item>
                           <item>Fol. <locus>7r</locus>: <q xml:lang="no">Einar <lb/> tabes</q>. </item>
                           <item>Fol. <locus>23r</locus>: <q xml:lang="no">þorarī nefiolfson førde
                                 hræræk k: til Jsland</q>. </item>
                           <item>Fol. <locus>23v</locus>: <q xml:lang="no">ewinder wrehorn</q>. </item>
                           <item>Fol. <locus>40v</locus>: <q xml:lang="no">Biarmalandsferd Karls
                                 gusteins brødra ok þore huds</q>. </item>
                           <item>Fol. <locus>41r</locus>: A hand points towards the text, and the
                              two marginal notes read: <q xml:lang="no">
                                 <hi rend="underline">jomali</hi>
                                 <lb/> biarma <lb/> gudh</q> and <q xml:lang="no">ganwick i
                                 finmorck</q>.</item>
                           <item>Fol. <locus>41v</locus>: <q xml:lang="no">geirswer</q>, <q
                                 xml:lang="no">Tore<lb/> hundir <lb/> drap <lb/> karll</q>, <q
                                 xml:lang="no">lengiowick</q>, and <q xml:lang="no">langó
                                 biarkóy</q>.</item>
                           <item>Fol. <locus>43r</locus>: <q xml:lang="no">Skat aff <lb/> island
                                 <lb/> Penin<hi rend="underline">g</hi>
                                 <lb/> for f <hi rend="underline">nef</hi>
                                 <lb/> huert <lb/> þan er X. <lb/> we f alin <lb/> wanmels</q>, <q
                                 xml:lang="no">Jamte <lb/> land oc <lb/> helsinge <lb/> land <lb/>
                                 bygdis</q>.</item>
                           <item>Fol. <locus>58v</locus>: <q xml:lang="no">
                                 <supplied reason="damage">Ari</supplied> p<ex>re</ex>stir <lb/>
                                 <supplied reason="damage">þorg</supplied>ilson <lb/>
                                 <supplied reason="damage">skr</supplied>eff sogu <lb/>
                                 <supplied reason="damage">Olaf</supplied>s hins <lb/>
                                 <supplied reason="damage">h</supplied>elge</q>. </item>
                        </list> The marginal notes on fols <locus>13r</locus>, <locus from="14"
                           to="14">14r-v</locus>, <locus>25v</locus>, <locus>27v</locus>,
                           <locus>31r</locus>, <locus>32r</locus>, <locus>34r</locus>,
                           <locus>36r</locus>, <locus>57v</locus> and <locus>59r</locus> are for the
                        most part illegible or partly cut away.</p>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding when="1935" contemporary="false">
                        <p>The manuscript was once bound in a grey cardboard binding. This was
                           replaced with a half binding with spine and corners of cloth and marbled
                           side-paper in the <date notBefore="1880" notAfter="1889">1880s</date>. A
                           rebinding took place in <date when="1935">1935</date> by <name
                              type="person" key="CarLun001">Carl Lund</name>, and now the manuscript
                           is bound in a parchment cover with the title in gold printed on the upper
                           board.</p>
                        <p>When <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni Magnússon</name> acquired
                           the manuscript, it was bound together with another manuscript (presumably
                           <ref type="ms" target="#AM04-0310-en">AM 310 4to</ref>) in one single volume; he separated
                           them into two. <name type="person" key="OleWor001">Ole Worm</name> has
                           made a list of contents on the first fly-leaf, which was cut away by Árni
                           Magnússon and pasted to fol. <locus>42r</locus> in his catalogue of
                           Icelandic parchment manuscripts, now known as <ref type="ms" target="#AM04-0435-a-en">AM 435 a
                              4to</ref>. It reads: <q xml:lang="la">In hoc libro continentur <lb/>
                              1. Sancti olai Regis historia <lb/> 2. Regum Norvagicorum res
                              gestæ.</q> Árni Magnússon has also written the following account in
                           the same place: <q xml:lang="is">Þesse bok er nu skild ad, og sin Sagan i
                              hveriu <lb/> Volumine, med þvi þær og voru med mig ö<lb
                                 rend="hyphenated"/>likum hndum.</q>
                        </p>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin notBefore="1300" notAfter="1350" cert="high" evidence="conjecture">
                     <p>The manuscript was written in <origPlace>Iceland</origPlace> in <origDate
                           notBefore="1300" notAfter="1350">the first half of the fourteenth
                           century</origDate>.</p>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>On the basis of an identification of the handwriting of the marginal notes,
                        Johnsen and Jón Helgason (<bibl>
                           <ref type="secondary" target="OlHJH">Den store Saga om Olav den
                              Hellige</ref>
                           <biblScope unit="pages">895</biblScope>
                        </bibl>) suggest that the Norwegian Lawman <name type="person"
                           key="JonSim001">Jón Simonson</name> of Agder in Southern
                           Norway, was the first
                        known owner of the codex. The codex was later brought to <name type="place"
                           key="Copen01" xml:lang="en">Copenhagen</name> together with <ref
                           type="ms">AM 310 4to</ref> and belonged to <name type="person"
                           key="OleWor001">Ole Worm</name> (the two manuscripts were bound together
                        within the same volume at that time). After the death of Ole Worm in <date
                           when="1654">1654</date>, the codex came into the possession of his son,
                           <name type="person" key="WilWor001">Villum Worm</name>. Fol. <locus>l
                           1v</locus> in <title>Resens Edda Islandorum</title> reads: <q
                           xml:lang="la">Olafs saga (historia S. Olai Regis qvæ MS. extat in
                           Bibliothecâ Wilh. Wormii</q>. Villum's son, <name type="person"
                           key="ChrWor001">Christen Worm</name>, was the next owner, and he gave the
                        codex to <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni Magnússon</name> in <date
                           when="1706">1706</date>. The original first fly-leaf contains a note
                        written by Ole Worm reading: <q xml:lang="la">In hoc libro continentur <lb/>
                           1. Sancti olai Regis historia <lb/> 2. Regum Norvagicorum res gestæ.</q>
                        This note was cut out by Árni Magnússon and pasted to fol. <locus>Ad
                           42r</locus> in <ref type="ms" target="#AM04-0435-a-en">AM 435 a 4to</ref>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>
                        <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni Magnússon</name> acquired the book
                        from <name type="person" key="ChrWor001">Christen Worm</name> in <date
                           when="1706">1706</date>. At that time it was bound together with <ref
                           type="ms">AM 310 4to</ref>. On fol. <locus>40v</locus> in <ref type="ms"
                           >AM 435 a 4to</ref> he writes: <q xml:lang="is">Olafs Saga Tryggvasonar
                           auctore <lb/>
                           <hi rend="underline">Oddo monacho.</hi>
                           <lb/> Olafs saga Helga. <lb/> 4to. Þennan Codicem feck <lb/> eg 1706. af
                              D<ex>omi</ex>no <name type="person" key="ChrWor001">christiano <lb/>
                              Wormio</name>. til eignar.</q> On fol. <locus>42r</locus> he adds: <q
                           xml:lang="is">Þesse bok er nu skild ad, og sin Sagan i hveriu <lb/>
                           Volumine, med þvi þær og voru med mig ö<lb rend="hyphenated"/>likum
                           hndum. Framan ä bokinne stöd <lb/> Doct. <name type="person"
                              key="OleWor001">olufs Worms</name> hnd, og hefr han<ex>n</ex> (qvod
                           <lb/> certum est) bokina ätt.</q>
                     </p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
